From bcaf0075fb49a8ad7fd5c9aaaae397d78c2dd958 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Pppery <mapreader@olum.org>
Date: Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:02:21 -0500
Subject: [PATCH 10/50] Continue on failure of various class map queries

Summary:
Fixes T15485

It's of course still possible to break your setup, but I think this means that if you're working on some third party extension you can't get into a chicken-egg problem where you delete a class and `arc liberate` tries to load this class so can't update the library map to no longer include the class.

I actually ran into the `PhutilTranslation` case when working on downstream code (For example https://gerrit.wikimedia.org/r/c/phabricator/translations/+/1217883). The others are for paranoia.

Test Plan:
Create a file with the following content:
```
<?php
class x extends ArcanistWorkingCopy {
  public function newWorkingCopyFromDirectories($a,$b) {}
  public function newRepositoryAPI() {}
}
class y extends ArcanistConfigurationEngineExtension {
  const EXTENSIONKEY = 'dummy';
  public function newConfigurationOptions() { return array(); }
}
class z extends PhutilLocale {
  public function getLocaleCode() {}
  public function getLocaleName() {}
}
class a extends ArcanistToolset {
  const TOOLSETKEY = 'dummy';
}
class b extends PhutilTranslation {
  public function getLocaleCode() {}
  public function getTranslations() {}
}
class c extends ArcanistWorkflow {
  public function getWorkflowName() {}
}
```

Run `arc liberate`.

Delete the file.

Run `arc liberate` again and see that it removes the file from the library map and doesn't complain.

(I added a print statement to PhutilClassMapQuery - these are the only classes it tries to instantiate)

